  "What does 'purchasing power' mean in the context of inflation (decay)?": "",
  "The current price of goods, particularly in the context of inflation": "",
  "The quantity of goods and services a unit of currency can buy, which decreases over time due to inflation": "",
  "Your credit card spending limit when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The total amount of money you have when considering all relevant inflation factors": "",
  "Purchasing power measures what your money can actually buy. Inflation acts as exponential decay on purchasing power: at 3% inflation, $100 buys 3% less goods each year.": "",
  "What does 'asymptote' mean in decay models?": "",
  "The starting value, particularly when asymptote considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "The maximum value because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "The average value over time, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "A value that the decaying function approaches but never actually reaches, typically zero in financial decay models": "",
  "In exponential decay, the value approaches zero but mathematically never reaches it (the x-axis is a horizontal asymptote). Practically, the value becomes negligibly small after enough time.": "",
  "What does 'real return' mean (adjusting growth for inflation decay)?": "",
  "The investment return after subtracting the inflation rate, showing actual purchasing power gain": "",
  "A guaranteed return from bonds regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "The return on real estate only, based on conventional assumptions about return": "",
  "The nominal return on an investment within the broader context of return analysis": "",
  "Real return ≈ nominal return - inflation rate. If your investment earns 8% but inflation is 3%, your real return is approximately 5% — the actual gain in purchasing power.": "",
